    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks for the tips. i think it might be a nitrogen thing though since the yellowing is pretty widespread on the bottom. how do i fix the soil to get more nitrogen back in there? and what should i check for with the ph levels?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "You're absolutely right about the nitrogen connection, and you can fix the soil by adding compost, manure, or a balanced fertilizer to replenish those essential nutrients. When it comes to pH levels, tomatoes generally thrive in slightly acidic soil between 6.0 and 6.8, so you might want to test your soil and adjust with lime if it's too acidic or sulfur if it's too alkaline.\n\nSpeaking of adjusting the soil, you could also try mixing in some nitrogen-rich side dishes like coffee grounds or eggshells to help boost the nitrogen content naturally. Just be careful not to overdo it, as too much nitrogen can actually lead to excessive leafy growth at the expense of fruit production.\n\nIf you're feeling adventurous, you could even set up a small compost bin in your garden to create a steady supply of nutrient-rich soil amendments. It's a great way to keep your plants healthy and your soil rich with all the necessary elements.\n\nOh, and don't forget to check for any pests that might be nibbling on your plants while you're fixing the soil. Sometimes, even a little bit of pest activity can cause yellowing leaves, so it's always good to keep an eye out for any signs",
